{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_d4e03412a73d4755b43b3d54","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t|github-actions| |coverage|\n2\t\n3\tAbout\n4\t=====\n5\t\n6\tCAN BUS tools in Python 3.\n7\t\n8\t- `DBC`_, `KCD`_, SYM, ARXML 3&4 and CDD file parsing.\n9\t\n10\t- CAN message encoding and decoding.\n11\t\n12\t- Simple and extended signal multiplexing.\n13\t\n14\t- Diagnostic DID encoding and decoding.\n15\t\n16\t- ``candump`` output decoder.\n17\t\n18\t- Node `tester`_.\n19\t\n20\t- `C` source code generator.\n21\t\n22\t- CAN bus monitor.\n23\t\n24\t- Graphical plots of signals.\n25\t\n26\tProject homepage: https://github.com/cantools/cantools\n27\t\n28\tDocumentation: https://cantools.readthedocs.io\n29\t\n30\tInstallation\n31\t============\n32\t\n33\t.. code-block:: bash\n34\t\n35\t    python3 -m pip install cantools\n36\t\n37\tExample usage\n38\t=============\n39\t\n40\tScripting\n41\t---------\n42\t\n43\tThe example starts by parsing a `small DBC-file`_ and printing its\n44\tmessages and signals.\n45\t\n46\t.. code-block:: python\n47\t\n48\t   >>> import cantools\n49\t   >>> from pprint import pprint\n50\t   >>> db = cantools.database.load_file('tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc')\n51\t   >>> db.messages\n52\t   [message('ExampleMessage', 0x1f0, False, 8, 'Example message used as template in MotoHawk models.')]\n53\t   >>> example_message = db.get_message_by_name('ExampleMessage')\n54\t   >>> pprint(example_message.signals)\n55\t   [signal('Enable', 7, 1, 'big_endian', False, 1.0, 0, 0.0, 0.0, '-', False, None, {0: 'Disabled', 1: 'Enabled'}, None),\n56\t    signal('AverageRadius', 6, 6, 'big_endian', False, 0.1, 0, 0.0, 5.0, 'm', False, None, None, ''),\n57\t    signal('Temperature', 0, 12, 'big_endian', True, 0.01, 250, 229.53, 270.47, 'degK', False, None, None, None)]\n58\t\n59\tThe example continues `encoding`_ a message and sending it on a CAN\n60\tbus using the `python-can`_ package.\n61\t\n62\t.. code-block:: python\n63\t\n64\t   >>> import can\n65\t   >>> can_bus = can.interface.Bus('vcan0', bustype='socketcan')\n66\t   >>> data = example_message.encode({'Temperature': 250.1, 'AverageRadius': 3.2, 'Enable': 1})\n67\t   >>> message = can.Message(arbitration_id=example_message.frame_id, is_extended_id=example_message.is_extended_frame, data=data)\n68\t   >>> can_bus.send(message)\n69\t\n70\tAlternatively, a message can be encoded using the `encode_message()`_\n71\tmethod on the database object.\n72\t\n73\tThe last part of the example receives and `decodes`_ a CAN message.\n74\t\n75\t.. code-block:: python\n76\t\n77\t   >>> message = can_bus.recv()\n78\t   >>> db.decode_message(message.arbitration_id, message.data)\n79\t   {'AverageRadius': 3.2, 'Enable': 'Enabled', 'Temperature': 250.09}\n80\t\n81\tSee `examples`_ for additional examples.\n82\t\n83\tCommand line tool\n84\t-----------------\n85\t\n86\tThe decode subcommand\n87\t^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n88\t\n89\tDecode CAN frames captured with the Linux program ``candump``.\n90\t\n91\t.. code-block:: text\n92\t\n93\t   $ candump vcan0 | python3 -m cantools decode tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n94\t     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n95\t   ExampleMessage(\n96\t       Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n97\t       AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n98\t       Temperature: 255.92 degK\n99\t   )\n100\t     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n101\t   ExampleMessage(\n102\t       Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n103\t       AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n104\t       Temperature: 255.92 degK\n105\t   )\n106\t     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n107\t   ExampleMessage(\n108\t       Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n109\t       AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n110\t       Temperature: 255.92 degK\n111\t   )\n112\t\n113\tAlternatively, the decoded message can be printed on a single line:\n114\t\n115\t.. code-block:: text\n116\t\n117\t   $ candump vcan0 | python3 -m cantools decode --single-line tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n118\t     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n119\t     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n120\t     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n121\t\n122\tThe plot subcommand\n123\t^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n124\t\n125\tThe plot subcommand is similar to the decode subcommand but messages are visualized using `matplotlib`_ instead of being printed to stdout.\n126\t\n127\t.. code-block:: bash\n128\t\n129\t    $ candump -l vcan0\n130\t    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log\n131\t    (1609779922.655421) vcan0 00000343#B204B9049C049C04\n132\t    (1609779922.655735) vcan0 0000024A#120527052E051905\n133\t    (1609779923.657524) vcan0 00000343#C404C404CB04C404\n134\t    (1609779923.658086) vcan0 0000024A#8B058B058B059205\n135\t    (1609779924.659912) vcan0 00000343#5C04790479045504\n136\t    (1609779924.660471) vcan0 0000024A#44064B0659064406\n137\t    (1609779925.662277) vcan0 00000343#15040704F203F203\n138\t    (1609779925.662837) vcan0 0000024A#8B069906A706A706\n139\t    (1609779926.664191) vcan0 00000343#BC03B503A703BC03\n140\t    (1609779926.664751) vcan0 0000024A#A006A706C406C406\n141\t\n142\t    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | python3 -m cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc\n143\t\n144\t.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-1.png\n145\t\n146\tIf you don't want to show all signals you can select the desired signals with command line arguments.\n147\tA ``*`` can stand for any number of any character, a ``?`` for exactly one arbitrary character.\n148\tSignals separated by a ``-`` are displayed in separate subplots.\n149\tOptionally a format can be specified after a signal, separated by a colon.\n150\t\n151\t.. code-block:: bash\n152\t\n153\t    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | python3 -m cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc '*33.*fl:-<' '*33.*fr:->' - '*33.*rl:-<' '*33.*rr:->'\n154\t\n155\t.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-2-subplots.png\n156\t\n157\tSignals with a different range of values can be displayed in the same subplot on different vertical axes by separating them with a comma.\n158\t\n159\t.. code-block:: bash\n160\t\n161\t   $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot --auto-color tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc -- \\\n162\t      --ylabel 'Bremse 33' '*_33.*fl*:-<' '*_33.*fr*:>' '*_33.*rl*:3' '*_33.*rr*:4' , \\\n163\t      --ylabel 'Bremse 2' '*_2.*fl*:-<' '*_2.*fr*:>' '*_2.*rl*:3' '*_2.*rr*:4'\n164\t\n165\t.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-2-axes.png\n166\t\n167\tMatplotlib comes with different preinstalled styles that you can use:\n168\t\n169\t.. code-block:: bash\n170\t\n171\t   $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc --style seaborn\n172\t\n173\t.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-seaborn.png\n174\t\n175\tYou can try all available styles with\n176\t\n177\t.. code-block:: bash\n178\t\n179\t   $ cantools plot --list-styles . | sed -n '/^- /s/^- //p' | while IFS= read -r style; do\n180\t         cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc --style \"$style\" --title \"--style '$style'\"\n181\t     done\n182\t\n183\tFor more information see\n184\t\n185\t.. code-block:: bash\n186\t\n187\t    $ python3 -m cantools plot --help\n188\t\n189\tNote that by default matplotlib is not installed with cantools. But it can be by specifying an extra\n190\tat installation:\n191\t\n192\t.. code-block:: bash\n193\t\n194\t    $ python3 -m pip install cantools[plot]\n195\t\n196\tThe dump subcommand\n197\t^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n198\t\n199\tDump given database in a human readable format:\n200\t\n201\t.. code-block:: text\n202\t\n203\t   $ python3 -m cantools dump tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n204\t   ================================= Messages =================================\n205\t\n206\t     ------------------------------------------------------------------------\n207\t\n208\t     Name:       ExampleMessage\n209\t     Id:         0x1f0\n210\t     Length:     8 bytes\n211\t     Cycle time: - ms\n212\t     Senders:    PCM1\n213\t     Layout:\n214\t\n215\t                             Bit\n216\t\n217\t                7   6   5   4   3   2   1   0\n218\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n219\t            0 |<-x|<---------------------x|<--|\n220\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n221\t                |                       +-- AverageRadius\n222\t                +-- Enable\n223\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n224\t            1 |-------------------------------|\n225\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n226\t            2 |----------x|   |   |   |   |   |\n227\t        B     +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n228\t        y               +-- Temperature\n229\t        t     +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n230\t        e   3 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n231\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n232\t            4 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n233\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n234\t            5 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n235\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n236\t            6 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n237\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n238\t            7 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n239\t              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n240\t\n241\t     Signal tree:\n242\t\n243\t       -- {root}\n244\t          +-- Enable\n245\t          +-- AverageRadius\n246\t          +-- Temperature\n247\t\n248\t     Signal choices:\n249\t\n250\t       Enable\n251\t           0 Disabled\n252\t           1 Enabled\n253\t\n254\t     ------------------------------------------------------------------------\n255\t\n256\tThe list subcommand\n257\t^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n258\t\n259\tPrint all information of a given database in a human readable\n260\tformat. This is very similar to the \"dump\" subcommand, but the output\n261\tis less pretty, slightly more comprehensive and easier to parse by\n262\tshell scripts:\n263\t\n264\t.. code-block:: bash\n265\t\n266\t    $ python3 -m cantools list -a tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n267\t    ExampleMessage:\n268\t      Comment[None]: Example message used as template in MotoHawk models.\n269\t      Frame ID: 0x1f0 (496)\n270\t      Size: 8 bytes\n271\t      Is extended frame: False\n272\t      Signals:\n273\t        Enable:\n274\t          Type: Integer\n275\t          Start bit: 7\n276\t          Length: 1 bits\n277\t          Unit: -\n278\t          Is signed: False\n279\t          Named values:\n280\t            0: Disabled\n281\t\n282\tThe generate C source subcommand\n283\t^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n284\t\n285\tGenerate `C` source code from given database.\n286\t\n287\tThe generated code contains:\n288\t\n289\t- Message `structs`_.\n290\t\n291\t- Message `pack`_ and `unpack`_ functions.\n292\t\n293\t- Signal `encode`_ and `decode`_ functions.\n294\t\n295\t- Frame id, length, type, cycle time and signal choices `defines`_.\n296\t\n297\tKnown limitations:\n298\t\n299\t- The maximum signal size is 64 bits, which in practice is never\n300\t  exceeded.\n301\t\n302\tBelow is an example of how to generate C source code from a\n303\tdatabase. The database is ``tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc``.\n304\t\n305\t.. code-block:: text\n306\t\n307\t   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n308\t   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n309\t\n310\tSee `motohawk.h`_ and `motohawk.c`_ for the contents of the generated\n311\tfiles.\n312\t\n313\tIn this example we use ``--use-float`` so floating point numbers in the generated\n314\tcode are single precision (``float``) instead of double precision (``double``).\n315\t\n316\t.. code-block:: text\n317\t\n318\t   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --use-float tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n319\t   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n320\t\n321\tIn the next example we use ``--database-name`` to set a custom\n322\tnamespace for all generated types, defines and functions. The output\n323\tfile names are also changed by this option.\n324\t\n325\t.. code-block:: text\n326\t\n327\t   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --database-name my_database_name tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n328\t   Successfully generated my_database_name.h and my_database_name.c.\n329\t\n330\tSee `my_database_name.h`_ and `my_database_name.c`_ for the contents\n331\tof the generated files.\n332\t\n333\tIn the next example we use ``--no-floating-point-numbers`` to generate\n334\tcode without floating point types, i.e. ``float`` and ``double``.\n335\t\n336\t.. code-block:: text\n337\t\n338\t   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --no-floating-point-numbers tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n339\t   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n340\t\n341\tSee `motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h`_ and\n342\t`motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c`_ for the contents of the\n343\tgenerated files.\n344\t\n345\tIn the last example ``--node`` is used to generate\n346\tmessage pack functions only for messages sent by the specified node and unpack\n347\tfunctions only for messages with its signal receivers belonging to that node. \n348\t\n349\t.. code-block:: text\n350\t\n351\t   $ cantools generate_c_source tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc --node PCM1\n352\t   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n353\t\n354\tSee `motohawk_sender_node.h`_ and\n355\t`motohawk_sender_node.c`_ for the contents of the\n356\tgenerated files.\n357\t\n358\tOther C code generators:\n359\t\n360\t- http://www.coderdbc.com\n361\t\n362\t- https://github.com/howerj/dbcc\n363\t\n364\t- https://github.com/lonkamikaze/hsk-libs/blob/master/scripts/dbc2c.awk\n365\t\n366\t- https://sourceforge.net/projects/comframe/\n367\t\n368\tThe monitor subcommand\n369\t^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n370\t\n371\tMonitor CAN bus traffic in a text based user interface.\n372\t\n373\t.. code-block:: text\n374\t\n375\t   $ python3 -m cantools monitor tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n376\t\n377\t.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/monitor.png\n378\t\n379\tThe menu at the bottom of the monitor shows the available commands.\n380\t\n381\t- Quit: Quit the monitor. Ctrl-C can be used as well.\n382\t\n383\t- Filter: Only display messages or signals matching given regular\n384\t  expression. Press <Enter> to return to the menu from the filter\n385\t  input line.\n386\t\n387\t- Play/Pause: Toggle between playing and paused (or running and freezed).\n388\t\n389\t- Reset: Reset the monitor to its initial state.\n390\t\n391\tContributing\n392\t============\n393\t\n394\t#. Fork the repository.\n395\t\n396\t#. Install prerequisites. You can skip this if you use `tox`_.\n397\t\n398\t   .. code-block:: text\n399\t\n400\t      python3 -m pip install -e .[dev]\n401\t\n402\t#. Implement the new feature or bug fix.\n403\t\n404\t#. Implement test case(s) to ensure that future changes do not break\n405\t   legacy.\n406\t\n407\t#. Run the linters\n408\t\n409\t   .. code-block:: text\n410\t\n411\t      ruff check src\n412\t      mypy src\n413\t\n414\t   or\n415\t\n416\t   .. code-block:: text\n417\t\n418\t      tox -e ruff\n419\t      tox -e mypy\n420\t\n421\t#. Run the tests.\n422\t\n423\t   .. code-block:: text\n424\t\n425\t      tox -e py\n426\t\n427\t#. Check test coverage.\n428\t\n429\t   .. code-block:: text\n430\t\n431\t      tox -e cov\n432\t      firefox htmlcov/index.html\n433\t\n434\t#. Create a pull request.\n435\t\n436\t.. |github-actions| image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/actions/workflows/pythonpackage.yml/badge.svg?branch=master\n437\t   :target: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/actions/workflows/pythonpackage.yml\n438\t   :alt: Github Actions workflow status\n439\t\n440\t.. |coverage| image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/cantools/cantools/badge.svg?branch=master\n441\t   :target: https://coveralls.io/github/cantoolscantools?branch=master\n442\t   :alt: Test coverage reports on Coveralls.io\n443\t\n444\t\n445\t.. _small DBC-file: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n446\t\n447\t.. _motohawk.dbc: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n448\t\n449\t.. _python-can: https://python-can.readthedocs.io/en/master/\n450\t\n451\t.. _DBC: http://www.socialledge.com/sjsu/index.php?title=DBC_Format\n452\t\n453\t.. _KCD: https://github.com/julietkilo/kcd\n454\t\n455\t.. _tester: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.tester.Tester\n456\t\n457\t.. _encoding: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Message.encode\n458\t\n459\t.. _encode_message(): http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Database.encode_message\n460\t\n461\t.. _decodes: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Database.decode_message\n462\t\n463\t.. _examples: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/examples\n464\t\n465\t.. _structs: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L58\n466\t\n467\t.. _pack: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L88\n468\t\n469\t.. _unpack: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L102\n470\t\n471\t.. _encode: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L116\n472\t\n473\t.. _decode: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L125\n474\t\n475\t.. _defines: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h#L42\n476\t\n477\t.. _motohawk.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.h\n478\t\n479\t.. _motohawk.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk.c\n480\t\n481\t.. _my_database_name.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/my_database_name.h\n482\t\n483\t.. _my_database_name.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/my_database_name.c\n484\t\n485\t.. _motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h\n486\t\n487\t.. _motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c\n488\t\n489\t.. _motohawk_sender_node.h: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_sender_node.h\n490\t\n491\t.. _motohawk_sender_node.c: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/c_source/motohawk_sender_node.c\n492\t\n493\t.. _matplotlib: https://matplotlib.org/\n494\t\n495\t.. _tox: http://tox.readthedocs.org/\n496\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c3b75779-49e8-47f1-ac5d-a21476a70ea5","uuid":"a48b542d-83a7-4d38-ac61-78c0a7ed2fa8","timestamp":"2026-04-06T20:36:05.376Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst","content":"|github-actions| |coverage|\n\nAbout\n=====\n\nCAN BUS tools in Python 3.\n\n- `DBC`_, `KCD`_, SYM, ARXML 3&4 and CDD file parsing.\n\n- CAN message encoding and decoding.\n\n- Simple and extended signal multiplexing.\n\n- Diagnostic DID encoding and decoding.\n\n- ``candump`` output decoder.\n\n- Node `tester`_.\n\n- `C` source code generator.\n\n- CAN bus monitor.\n\n- Graphical plots of signals.\n\nProject homepage: https://github.com/cantools/cantools\n\nDocumentation: https://cantools.readthedocs.io\n\nInstallation\n============\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    python3 -m pip install cantools\n\nExample usage\n=============\n\nScripting\n---------\n\nThe example starts by parsing a `small DBC-file`_ and printing its\nmessages and signals.\n\n.. code-block:: python\n\n   >>> import cantools\n   >>> from pprint import pprint\n   >>> db = cantools.database.load_file('tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc')\n   >>> db.messages\n   [message('ExampleMessage', 0x1f0, False, 8, 'Example message used as template in MotoHawk models.')]\n   >>> example_message = db.get_message_by_name('ExampleMessage')\n   >>> pprint(example_message.signals)\n   [signal('Enable', 7, 1, 'big_endian', False, 1.0, 0, 0.0, 0.0, '-', False, None, {0: 'Disabled', 1: 'Enabled'}, None),\n    signal('AverageRadius', 6, 6, 'big_endian', False, 0.1, 0, 0.0, 5.0, 'm', False, None, None, ''),\n    signal('Temperature', 0, 12, 'big_endian', True, 0.01, 250, 229.53, 270.47, 'degK', False, None, None, None)]\n\nThe example continues `encoding`_ a message and sending it on a CAN\nbus using the `python-can`_ package.\n\n.. code-block:: python\n\n   >>> import can\n   >>> can_bus = can.interface.Bus('vcan0', bustype='socketcan')\n   >>> data = example_message.encode({'Temperature': 250.1, 'AverageRadius': 3.2, 'Enable': 1})\n   >>> message = can.Message(arbitration_id=example_message.frame_id, is_extended_id=example_message.is_extended_frame, data=data)\n   >>> can_bus.send(message)\n\nAlternatively, a message can be encoded using the `encode_message()`_\nmethod on the database object.\n\nThe last part of the example receives and `decodes`_ a CAN message.\n\n.. code-block:: python\n\n   >>> message = can_bus.recv()\n   >>> db.decode_message(message.arbitration_id, message.data)\n   {'AverageRadius': 3.2, 'Enable': 'Enabled', 'Temperature': 250.09}\n\nSee `examples`_ for additional examples.\n\nCommand line tool\n-----------------\n\nThe decode subcommand\n^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n\nDecode CAN frames captured with the Linux program ``candump``.\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ candump vcan0 | python3 -m cantools decode tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n   ExampleMessage(\n       Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n       AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n       Temperature: 255.92 degK\n   )\n     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n   ExampleMessage(\n       Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n       AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n       Temperature: 255.92 degK\n   )\n     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 ::\n   ExampleMessage(\n       Enable: 'Enabled' -,\n       AverageRadius: 0.0 m,\n       Temperature: 255.92 degK\n   )\n\nAlternatively, the decoded message can be printed on a single line:\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ candump vcan0 | python3 -m cantools decode --single-line tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n     vcan0  1F0   [8]  80 4A 0F 00 00 00 00 00 :: ExampleMessage(Enable: 'Enabled' -, AverageRadius: 0.0 m, Temperature: 255.92 degK)\n\nThe plot subcommand\n^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n\nThe plot subcommand is similar to the decode subcommand but messages are visualized using `matplotlib`_ instead of being printed to stdout.\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    $ candump -l vcan0\n    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log\n    (1609779922.655421) vcan0 00000343#B204B9049C049C04\n    (1609779922.655735) vcan0 0000024A#120527052E051905\n    (1609779923.657524) vcan0 00000343#C404C404CB04C404\n    (1609779923.658086) vcan0 0000024A#8B058B058B059205\n    (1609779924.659912) vcan0 00000343#5C04790479045504\n    (1609779924.660471) vcan0 0000024A#44064B0659064406\n    (1609779925.662277) vcan0 00000343#15040704F203F203\n    (1609779925.662837) vcan0 0000024A#8B069906A706A706\n    (1609779926.664191) vcan0 00000343#BC03B503A703BC03\n    (1609779926.664751) vcan0 0000024A#A006A706C406C406\n\n    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | python3 -m cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-1.png\n\nIf you don't want to show all signals you can select the desired signals with command line arguments.\nA ``*`` can stand for any number of any character, a ``?`` for exactly one arbitrary character.\nSignals separated by a ``-`` are displayed in separate subplots.\nOptionally a format can be specified after a signal, separated by a colon.\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | python3 -m cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc '*33.*fl:-<' '*33.*fr:->' - '*33.*rl:-<' '*33.*rr:->'\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-2-subplots.png\n\nSignals with a different range of values can be displayed in the same subplot on different vertical axes by separating them with a comma.\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n   $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot --auto-color tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc -- \\\n      --ylabel 'Bremse 33' '*_33.*fl*:-<' '*_33.*fr*:>' '*_33.*rl*:3' '*_33.*rr*:4' , \\\n      --ylabel 'Bremse 2' '*_2.*fl*:-<' '*_2.*fr*:>' '*_2.*rl*:3' '*_2.*rr*:4'\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-2-axes.png\n\nMatplotlib comes with different preinstalled styles that you can use:\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n   $ cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc --style seaborn\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/plot-seaborn.png\n\nYou can try all available styles with\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n   $ cantools plot --list-styles . | sed -n '/^- /s/^- //p' | while IFS= read -r style; do\n         cat candump-2021-01-04_180521.log | cantools plot tests/files/dbc/abs.dbc --style \"$style\" --title \"--style '$style'\"\n     done\n\nFor more information see\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    $ python3 -m cantools plot --help\n\nNote that by default matplotlib is not installed with cantools. But it can be by specifying an extra\nat installation:\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    $ python3 -m pip install cantools[plot]\n\nThe dump subcommand\n^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n\nDump given database in a human readable format:\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ python3 -m cantools dump tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n   ================================= Messages =================================\n\n     ------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n     Name:       ExampleMessage\n     Id:         0x1f0\n     Length:     8 bytes\n     Cycle time: - ms\n     Senders:    PCM1\n     Layout:\n\n                             Bit\n\n                7   6   5   4   3   2   1   0\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            0 |<-x|<---------------------x|<--|\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n                |                       +-- AverageRadius\n                +-- Enable\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            1 |-------------------------------|\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            2 |----------x|   |   |   |   |   |\n        B     +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n        y               +-- Temperature\n        t     +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n        e   3 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            4 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            5 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            6 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n            7 |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |   |\n              +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+\n\n     Signal tree:\n\n       -- {root}\n          +-- Enable\n          +-- AverageRadius\n          +-- Temperature\n\n     Signal choices:\n\n       Enable\n           0 Disabled\n           1 Enabled\n\n     ------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nThe list subcommand\n^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n\nPrint all information of a given database in a human readable\nformat. This is very similar to the \"dump\" subcommand, but the output\nis less pretty, slightly more comprehensive and easier to parse by\nshell scripts:\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    $ python3 -m cantools list -a tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n    ExampleMessage:\n      Comment[None]: Example message used as template in MotoHawk models.\n      Frame ID: 0x1f0 (496)\n      Size: 8 bytes\n      Is extended frame: False\n      Signals:\n        Enable:\n          Type: Integer\n          Start bit: 7\n          Length: 1 bits\n          Unit: -\n          Is signed: False\n          Named values:\n            0: Disabled\n\nThe generate C source subcommand\n^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n\nGenerate `C` source code from given database.\n\nThe generated code contains:\n\n- Message `structs`_.\n\n- Message `pack`_ and `unpack`_ functions.\n\n- Signal `encode`_ and `decode`_ functions.\n\n- Frame id, length, type, cycle time and signal choices `defines`_.\n\nKnown limitations:\n\n- The maximum signal size is 64 bits, which in practice is never\n  exceeded.\n\nBelow is an example of how to generate C source code from a\ndatabase. The database is ``tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc``.\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n\nSee `motohawk.h`_ and `motohawk.c`_ for the contents of the generated\nfiles.\n\nIn this example we use ``--use-float`` so floating point numbers in the generated\ncode are single precision (``float``) instead of double precision (``double``).\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --use-float tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n\nIn the next example we use ``--database-name`` to set a custom\nnamespace for all generated types, defines and functions. The output\nfile names are also changed by this option.\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --database-name my_database_name tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n   Successfully generated my_database_name.h and my_database_name.c.\n\nSee `my_database_name.h`_ and `my_database_name.c`_ for the contents\nof the generated files.\n\nIn the next example we use ``--no-floating-point-numbers`` to generate\ncode without floating point types, i.e. ``float`` and ``double``.\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ python3 -m cantools generate_c_source --no-floating-point-numbers tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n\nSee `motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.h`_ and\n`motohawk_no_floating_point_numbers.c`_ for the contents of the\ngenerated files.\n\nIn the last example ``--node`` is used to generate\nmessage pack functions only for messages sent by the specified node and unpack\nfunctions only for messages with its signal receivers belonging to that node. \n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ cantools generate_c_source tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc --node PCM1\n   Successfully generated motohawk.h and motohawk.c.\n\nSee `motohawk_sender_node.h`_ and\n`motohawk_sender_node.c`_ for the contents of the\ngenerated files.\n\nOther C code generators:\n\n- http://www.coderdbc.com\n\n- https://github.com/howerj/dbcc\n\n- https://github.com/lonkamikaze/hsk-libs/blob/master/scripts/dbc2c.awk\n\n- https://sourceforge.net/projects/comframe/\n\nThe monitor subcommand\n^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^\n\nMonitor CAN bus traffic in a text based user interface.\n\n.. code-block:: text\n\n   $ python3 -m cantools monitor tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/raw/master/docs/monitor.png\n\nThe menu at the bottom of the monitor shows the available commands.\n\n- Quit: Quit the monitor. Ctrl-C can be used as well.\n\n- Filter: Only display messages or signals matching given regular\n  expression. Press <Enter> to return to the menu from the filter\n  input line.\n\n- Play/Pause: Toggle between playing and paused (or running and freezed).\n\n- Reset: Reset the monitor to its initial state.\n\nContributing\n============\n\n#. Fork the repository.\n\n#. Install prerequisites. You can skip this if you use `tox`_.\n\n   .. code-block:: text\n\n      python3 -m pip install -e .[dev]\n\n#. Implement the new feature or bug fix.\n\n#. Implement test case(s) to ensure that future changes do not break\n   legacy.\n\n#. Run the linters\n\n   .. code-block:: text\n\n      ruff check src\n      mypy src\n\n   or\n\n   .. code-block:: text\n\n      tox -e ruff\n      tox -e mypy\n\n#. Run the tests.\n\n   .. code-block:: text\n\n      tox -e py\n\n#. Check test coverage.\n\n   .. code-block:: text\n\n      tox -e cov\n      firefox htmlcov/index.html\n\n#. Create a pull request.\n\n.. |github-actions| image:: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/actions/workflows/pythonpackage.yml/badge.svg?branch=master\n   :target: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/actions/workflows/pythonpackage.yml\n   :alt: Github Actions workflow status\n\n.. |coverage| image:: https://coveralls.io/repos/github/cantools/cantools/badge.svg?branch=master\n   :target: https://coveralls.io/github/cantoolscantools?branch=master\n   :alt: Test coverage reports on Coveralls.io\n\n\n.. _small DBC-file: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n\n.. _motohawk.dbc: https://github.com/cantools/cantools/blob/master/tests/files/dbc/motohawk.dbc\n\n.. _python-can: https://python-can.readthedocs.io/en/master/\n\n.. _DBC: http://www.socialledge.com/sjsu/index.php?title=DBC_Format\n\n.. _KCD: https://github.com/julietkilo/kcd\n\n.. _tester: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.tester.Tester\n\n.. _encoding: http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Message.encode\n\n.. _encode_message(): http://cantools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/#cantools.database.can.Database.encode_message\n\n.. _decodes: http